<p class="drop-cap">The Western Church calls them sacraments, sacred signs that effect what they signify. The Eastern Church calls them <strong>Mysteries</strong>, and the difference in terminology is not accidental. A sacrament, in the popular Western imagination, can sometimes feel like a transaction: the right words are said, the right matter is used, and grace is dispensed. A Mystery is an encounter. Something experienced, entered into, and never fully comprehended. The Eastern Church does not claim to understand <em>how</em> bread becomes the Body of Christ. It simply confesses that it does, falls to its knees, and gives thanks.</p>

<p>Seven Mysteries: Baptism, <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#chrismation">Chrismation</a>, Eucharist, Confession, Marriage, Holy Orders, and <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#holy-unction">Holy Unction</a>. Each one addresses a different dimension of human life. Together, they form a comprehensive therapy for the whole person, body, soul, and spirit, from birth to death and beyond.</p>

<h2>The Three Mysteries of Initiation</h2>

<p>Here is something that surprises many Western Christians: in the Eastern tradition, Baptism, Chrismation, and the Eucharist are administered <em>together</em>, in a single service, even to infants. A baby baptized on a Sunday morning will, within the same hour, be chrismated with holy oil and receive Communion, the Body and Blood of Christ on a tiny golden spoon.</p>

<p>The logic is simple. If Baptism makes you a member of the Body of Christ, and the Eucharist is the food of that Body, then why withhold the food from a new member? The East does not require understanding as a prerequisite for grace. An infant does not understand mother's milk either, but no one withholds it on that account.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. John Chrysostom, Baptismal Instructions, 4th century">
  You were led to the sacred pool of divine Baptism, as Christ was led from the Cross to the Tomb. And each of you was asked whether you believed. And you confessed your faith — and descended three times into the water, and rose again.
</Pullquote>

<h3>Baptism</h3>

<p><strong>Baptism</strong> is death and resurrection. The candidate, infant or adult, is immersed three times in blessed water, in the name of the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit. Triple immersion as burial: going down into the waters of death with Christ. The rising is a resurrection: emerging into new life. The white garment placed on the newly baptized signifies the "new self" put on in Christ.</p>

<p>Full immersion is the Eastern norm, and it is considered theologically important. The symbolism of burial and rising is lost if water is merely poured. The water itself has been blessed by the <a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#epiklesis">epiklesis</a>, the invocation of the Holy Spirit, making it a new Jordan, a new Red Sea, a passage from slavery to freedom.</p>

