<h3>Chrismation</h3>

<p><strong><a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#chrismation">Chrismation</a></strong> immediately follows Baptism. The priest anoints the newly baptized with <em>holy chrism</em>, a specially consecrated oil blessed by the bishop, making the sign of the cross on the forehead, eyes, nostrils, lips, ears, chest, hands, and feet. At each anointing: "The seal of the gift of the Holy Spirit."</p>

<p>This is the Eastern equivalent of Confirmation, but it is not delayed until adolescence. The Spirit does not wait for intellectual maturity. The whole person, every sense, every faculty, is claimed for God from the very beginning.</p>

<h3>Eucharist</h3>

<p>The newly baptized and chrismated Christian then receives the <strong>Eucharist</strong>, the Body and Blood of Christ under the forms of bread and wine. This is the climax of initiation and the ongoing center of Christian life. In the Eastern tradition, the Eucharist is received from a spoon that contains both the consecrated bread and wine together, a practice called <em>intinction</em>.</p>

<p>The Eucharist is not an optional devotion. It is the food of immortality, the medicine of the soul, the real presence of Christ entering the communicant's body. To receive the Eucharist is to be united, physically, sacramentally, mystically, with the risen Lord.</p>

<h2>Confession: The Return</h2>

<p><strong>Confession</strong> (also called the Mystery of Repentance) is not a courtroom procedure. In the Eastern practice, penitent and priest stand together before an icon of Christ. The priest is a witness, not a judge. A physician diagnosing the illness, not a magistrate pronouncing sentence. The prayer of absolution asks God to "forgive, remit, and pardon" the sins confessed, and to "reconcile and unite" the penitent to the Church.</p>

<p>The penances assigned, additional prayer, fasting, prostrations, acts of mercy, are therapeutic, not punitive. Exercises designed to strengthen the weakened spiritual muscles that allowed the sin in the first place.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— St. Ignatius of Antioch, Letter to the Ephesians 20 (ANF translation, c. 107 AD)">
  …breaking one and the same bread, which is the medicine of immortality, and the antidote to prevent us from dying, but which causes that we should live forever in Jesus Christ.
</Pullquote>

<h2>Marriage: The Little Church</h2>

<p><strong>Marriage</strong> in the East is called the "crowning," because the bride and groom are literally crowned during the ceremony. The crowns symbolize both the glory of the marital vocation and the martyrdom it entails (the crowns are martyrs' crowns as much as royal ones). Marriage is understood as a path to theosis, the spouses helping each other grow toward God through the daily sacrifices of shared life.</p>

<p>The Eastern marriage service contains no vows.</p>

<p>The couple does not promise each other anything in words. They are crowned by the Church, and the crowning itself is the sacramental act. God joins them; they do not join themselves. The family they create is called the "little church" (<em>ecclesia domestica</em>), a microcosm of the larger Church with its own prayers, its own icons, its own rhythm of fasting and feasting.</p>

<h2>Holy Orders: Serving at the Altar</h2>

<p><strong>Holy Orders</strong> is the Mystery by which men are ordained to the diaconate, the priesthood, or the episcopate. Ordination takes place during the Divine Liturgy, in the presence of the assembled community, because ministry is not a private appointment. It is a public commissioning by the Church.</p>

<p>Married men may be ordained deacons and priests in the Eastern tradition. Bishops are chosen from among celibate clergy. This is not a theological principle but an ancient disciplinary practice, and it has given the Eastern Church a married parish clergy quite different in character from the celibate Latin priesthood.</p>

<h2>Holy Unction: Healing of Body and Soul</h2>

<p><strong><a href="/byzantine-doors/glossary/#holy-unction">Holy Unction</a></strong> is the anointing of the sick, and not only the dying. In the Eastern tradition, it is administered not as "Last Rites" (a common misconception) but as a prayer for healing that can be received multiple times throughout life. During Great Lent, many parishes offer a communal service of Holy Unction for all the faithful, recognizing that everyone carries some wound in need of the divine Physician's touch.</p>

<p>The service is beautiful and elaborate: seven Epistle readings, seven Gospel readings, seven anointings with blessed oil. The number seven signifies completeness. The whole person, in every dimension, presented to God for healing.</p>

