<h2>Mystery, Not Magic</h2>

<p>A final word about how the East understands the Mysteries. They are not magical formulas. They do not work automatically, independent of the faith and disposition of the participants. A person who receives the Eucharist without repentance does not receive grace; as St. Paul warned in 1 Corinthians 11, such a person receives judgment. A confession without genuine contrition is empty words.</p>

<p>But neither are the Mysteries merely symbols, beautiful rituals that point to a spiritual reality happening elsewhere. The East insists that the Mysteries are <em>real encounters</em> with God. The bread really becomes the Body. The water really regenerates. The oil really heals. The physical and the spiritual are not separate categories in Eastern thought; they interpenetrate, and the Mysteries are the places where this interpenetration is most visible.</p>

<p>This is why the East calls them Mysteries and not merely sacraments. They cannot be fully explained. They can only be entered into, with faith, with repentance, with awe, and experienced.</p>

<p>The next step moves from what Byzantine Christians believe to how they live, beginning with prayer: the breath of the spiritual life, and the practice that sustains everything else.</p>

